// =============================================================================
// tests/fixtures/sdk-matrix-locator/builtin_only.crush  [FIXTURE]
//
// Structural-lockstep fixture for
//   crush-pkg/tests/test_selfhost_sdk_matrix.rs
// Matrix ticket: TICKETS/CRUSH-SELFHOST-1.md
//
// CELL 4 (built-in cap) — **dedicated isolation**.
//
// CELL 4 ALSO fires from inside `main.crush` (the multi-cap fixture,
// via `io.print("builtin-caps-fire-from-source")`), so this dedicated
// preset uses a UNIQUE sentinel `"cell_4_dedicated_isolation"` so a
// reviewer running `git grep cell_4_dedicated_isolation` lands AT the
// dedicated isolation path (not the shared multi-cap one) — sentinel
// disambiguation by name.
//
// Attribution rationale. CELL 4 is fired from inside `main.crush`
// too — `io.print("builtin-caps-fire-from-source")` is one of the
// four cap-side cell calls there. But that fires WITHIN a program
// that ALSO calls user-extended caps (`capsule.cell_1`,
// `capsule.cell_3`, `repl_runtime.cell_5`). To attribute a CELL 4
// regression CONCLUSIVELY to the built-in registry (and NOT to the
// host-table plumbing), the matrix test isolates CELL 4 via this
// dedicated, built-in-only fixture driven by
// `run_with_caps(&program, &quotas, None)`:
//
//   * The program calls ONLY `io.print(...)` — no user-extended cap.
//   * `host_caps: None` is passed to `run_with_caps` so a registry
//     gap on `io.print` surfaces as the VM NOT reaching the output,
//     regardless of host-table state.
//   * The expected output sentinel `cell_4_dedicated_isolation` is
//     UNIQUE to this fixture (not shared with `main.crush`); a
//     regression in either the built-in registry OR the VM's `PRINT`
//     opcode path fails the same assert.
//
// Cross-link. CELL 4-in-main (the multi-cap flow that fires
// `io.print("builtin-caps-fire-from-source")` from inside `main.crush`)
// is **compile-reachable** but coarse-grained:
//   (a) CELL 7's `assert!(!program_via_compile.code.is_empty())` confirms
//       `main.crush` parsed + compile emitted SOME bytecode; this does
//       NOT verify that the io.print statement specifically produced
//       its own PRINT opcode (a regression that degraded io.print to
//       a no-op opcode would still pass the `code.is_empty()` check
//       as long as OTHER statements in fn main() emitted opcodes).
//   (b) Statement-level reachability in main.crush is implicit: if a
//       statement in `fn main()` fails, `CrushRunner::run(...)` either
//       panics on `.expect(...)` OR halts mid-fn, which means the cap
//       capturer carries fewer than the expected 3 cell-capturer-recorded
//       calls (`capsule.cell_1`, `capsule.cell_3`, `repl_runtime.cell_5`).
//       `io.print` itself is invisible to the capturer (built-in caps
//       dispatch through `crush-vm::caps::capabilities`, not via
//       `HostCap::call`), so the capturer is a PARTIAL per-statement
//       signal — fine for CELLS 1, 3, 5; insufficient for CELL 4.
//
// The dedicated isolation in this fixture gives CELL 4 the only explicit,
// fine-grained regression guard — a per-statement sentinel assertion
// via `run_with_caps(&program, &quotas, None)`.
//
// The compact 1-line program body fits `cat`-discoverability for
// review-by-cell (matrix ticket claim: "a reviewer can `cat` the
// fixture and read the cell references inline").
// =============================================================================

fn main() {
    io.print("cell_4_dedicated_isolation")
}
